   <div><div><br></div><div dir=3D"ltr">Kenneth Stanley and I are pleased t=

in Indirectly Encoded and Evolving Topographic Maps"<br><br><b>PDF: </=
b><a href=3D"http://eplex.cs.ucf.edu/papers/risi_gecco14.pdf" target=3D"_bl=
ank">http://eplex.cs.ucf.edu/papers/risi_gecco14.pdf</a><br>

<br>This pape=
r introduces the idea that HyperNEAT can be seeded with a lateral inhibitor=
y connectivity pattern, which then allows the weights from the inputs to th=
e hidden layer=C2=A0of an ANN to self-organize to form a genuine topographi=
c map of the input=C2=A0space. The benefit of this new approach is that the=
 initial seed can=C2=A0be evolved further to accelerate the self-organizing=
 process and to=C2=A0bias it towards a specific target configuration. An in=
teresting implication=C2=A0is that enabling HyperNEAT to capture this key f=
eature of=C2=A0natural systems might now allow us to evolve architectures r=
esembling=C2=A0deep learning networks, SOMs, or other self-organizing proce=
sses that also rely on unsupervised learning processes.<br>

<br><b>Abstrac=
t: </b>An important phenomenon seen in many areas of biological brains and =
recently in deep learning architectures is a process known as self-organiza=
tion. For example, in the primary visual cortex, color and orientation maps=
 develop based on lateral inhibitory connectivity patterns and Hebbian lear=
ning dynamics. These topographic maps, which are found in all sensory syste=
ms, are thought to be a key factor in enabling abstract cognitive represent=
ations. This paper shows for the first time that the Hypercube-based NeuroE=
volution of Augmenting Topologies (HyperNEAT) method can be seeded to begin=
 evolution =C2=A0with such lateral connectivity, enabling genuine self-orga=
nizing dynamics. The proposed approach draws on HyperNEAT's ability to =
generate a pattern of weights across the connectivity of an artificial neur=
al network (ANN) based on a function of its geometry. Validating this appro=
ach, the afferent weights of an ANN self-organize in this paper to form a g=
enuine topographic map of the input space for a simple line orientation tas=
k. Most interestingly, this seed can then be evolved further, providing a m=
ethod to guide the self-organization of weights in a specific way, much as =
evolution likely guided the self-organizing trajectories of biological brai=
ns.<br>
